b"Sandra Manay of Luna Sundara sells aromatherapy and home goods inspired by her Peruvian roots. b'Amazon stands in solidarity with the Black community \xe2\x80\x94 we remain steadfast in our support for our employees, customers, partners, and the communities where they live and work. And we stand in support of organizations that are making a difference. Link in bio.'

b'Mother\xe2\x80\x99s Day may feel different this year, but celebrating incredible moms hasn\xe2\x80\x99t changed. Meet some of our own moms at Amazon who are shipping and delivering critical items and taking care of kids and families at home. Thank you to all moms at Amazon for serving your community, and #HappyMothersDay! Tag a special mom in your life and tell us something about her :heart_exclamation:
...
Johany manages the schedules of 250 associates at work and helps her 7-year-old with school assignments at home - and is 21 weeks pregnant! Thank you Johany! :cherry_blossom:
...
Dallas is a working mom of six. She spends her days training new employees and her evenings homeschooling her kids. \xe2\x80\x9cI\xe2\x80\x99m proud to be working right now. I know others, especially high-risk individuals, are counting on us to deliver items they need.\xe2\x80\x9d Thank you Dallas! :cherry_blossom:
...
Maria is a single mother of five who works to make sure associates are healthy and safe, and orders are picked and packed correctly in Houston, TX. This weekend, she\xe2\x80\x99s enjoying a BBQ with her kids. Thank you Maria! :cherry_blossom:
...
Quanique started her own company delivering packages and is now one of our delivery service partners. \xe2\x80\x9cI have a daughter who looks to me as a role model for everything that she can do and be in this world.\xe2\x80\x9d Thank you Quanique! :cherry_blossom:'

b'In support of #BlackHistoryMonth we raised the Pan African flag on our Seattle campus last week in partnership with our Black Employee Network (BEN) to celebrate the importance of the flag and to honor black history.
.
.
.
Ian Wilson, VP of AWS HR, was present and delivered a strong message stating, \xe2\x80\x9cFor Black and African members of the Amazon community, we hope that this flag tells you that we see you, that we value you and that we\xe2\x80\x99re in it with you as we make progress together. And for other Amazonians, we hope that this flag is a reminder to learn and be curious about Black history. It was a time of pride, reflection, and awareness.\xe2\x80\x9d The flag will be in the plaza for the remainder of February and is open to the public. We encourage you to stop by and take a picture! Be sure to use the hashtag, #InsideAmazonxBHM2020'
